    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="419"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d419">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.796/7–2144</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of the Belgian Embassy</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gruben</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Assistant Secretary of State</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Berle</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">D.8443/8 <lb/> No. 3516</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-21">21 July,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Berle</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the
                    exchange of views between yourself and the Ambassador (who is now on leave) and
                    particularly to your letter of June 3, 1944 concerning informal conversations
                    between the Department of State and representatives of the Belgian Government on
                    post-war planning for commercial aviation.</p>
                <p>I am now informed that my Government has decided upon the general outlines of its
                    policy on this matter and that I will receive instructions in view of the
                    proposed conversations. I will not fail to inform you as soon as I will receive
                    them in order to initiate without further delays the exploratory discussions
                    suggested by the Department.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hervé de Gruben</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
